Brand Foundation

What a Good Brand Does

01
Standing out from Competitors
Why this matters
When your brand looks different from your competitors, people see your offering as a different product. They stop comparing you side by side. A distinct brand changes how people value what you sell — you go from being one of many options to being in a category of your own.
How we achieve this
We look at what every competitor does with their brand — the colours they pick, the logo styles they use, the fonts they choose — and we do the opposite. Then we make sure the result still connects with the people you want to reach.
02
Being remembered by your ideal Clients
Why this matters
When someone remembers your brand, it starts to feel familiar. Familiarity builds trust. The easier it is to recall your brand, the more natural it feels each time they come across it. That sense of "I know these guys" is a shortcut to trust — and trust wins work.
How we achieve this
We keep logos simple, easy to understand, and visually distinct. A mark that someone can picture from memory is a mark that's doing its job.
03
Creating a positive first impression
Why this matters
95% of how people feel about your brand comes from your work — your delivery, your marketing, your sales presentations. But we can still get a small edge by making a brand that people feel good about before they've even spoken to you.
How we achieve this
We can't measure exactly how someone feels about a visual. But we can take cues from brands your ideal clients already like and trust — borrowing the visual style of brands they already have a connection with.

What we see — and how to break the pattern

Three patterns show up again and again across these competitors. Here's what they are and what we recommend instead.

Pattern — Blue colour palettes everywhere
Nearly every competitor uses navy, royal blue, or cyan. It's meant to say "technology" and "trust" but it creates a wall of sameness.

Our recommendation: Use warm earth tones — burnt orange, ironbark red, olive — that show capability and Australian identity without falling into the same blue as everyone else.
Pattern — Security symbols in logos
Shields, locks, keys, and checkmarks appear across most competitors. They say "security" on the surface but don't set anyone apart.

Our recommendation: Use a logo that is visually distinct and not overcomplicated. A simple, unique mark is easier to remember and harder to confuse with everyone else in the space.
Pattern — Generic corporate fonts
Most competitors use safe, interchangeable sans-serif fonts — the kind you'd find on any enterprise website. Nothing stands out, nothing sticks.

Our recommendation: Pick a font system with real character. Something that feels intentional and distinct — not just another corporate sans-serif that blends into the background.
Deep Dive

Creating a positive first impression

Your two ideal client types respond to different brand signals. These are the brands each group already trusts — and the visual principles we can learn from them.

The Manufacturer
MD / Owner, $5M–$50M precision engineering
Hilti
Festool
Milwaukee
Makita
Bosch Professional
✓
What these brands do
  • Bold, industrial colour palettes — reds, blacks, yellows that signal toughness
  • Imagery focused on the product in action — real tools, real environments
  • Heavy, built-to-last typography that feels engineered, not decorative
✗
What they avoid
  • Soft, pastel palettes or overly polished corporate looks
  • Stock photography or generic lifestyle imagery
  • Lightweight, thin typography that feels fragile
The Innovator
CTO / Co-Founder, $2M–$15M deep-tech
Stripe
Figma
Linear
Notion
Vercel
✓
What these brands do
  • Minimal, geometric logos that feel modern and intentional
  • Restrained colour palettes — often monochrome with a single accent
  • Generous whitespace and clean layouts that show confidence
  • Precise, system-level typography built for digital
✗
What they avoid
  • Overly decorated or ornamental visual elements
  • Busy, cluttered layouts with too many competing elements
  • Loud colour schemes that feel aggressive rather than confident
  • Traditional corporate branding that feels outdated
Brand Element 01

Colour Palettes

Three palettes, each measured against the three things a good brand needs to do.

Industrial Warm
#0F1B2D
#D4792C
#1B3A54
#F2EDE4
Navy · Burnt Orange · Steel · Warm White
Standing out
The orange is a strong point of difference — almost no competitor uses warm tones. The navy base is common in the industry though, which pulls back some distinctiveness.
Being remembered
The navy-orange pair is familiar enough to feel professional, but different enough to stick. Good recall through strong contrast.
First impression
Feels approachable and professional. The warmth says "we care about relationships, not just compliance." Works well with both Manufacturers and Innovators.
Red Earth Defence
#1E1E1E
#8B3A2A
#3A6B52
#EDE8DE
Charcoal · Ironbark · Eucalypt · Sandstone
Standing out
The most distinctive palette of the three. No competitor uses earth tones. The Australian landscape reference is completely unique and ownable.
Being remembered
Very memorable because it's so unexpected in cyber. People will remember "the one with the red and green" because nothing else looks like it.
First impression
May feel too earthy for some clients. The charcoal-ironbark combination reads as serious and grounded, but could feel heavy. Likely connects more with Manufacturers than Innovators.
Operational Khaki
#3B432A
#A8883A
#5C6347
#F0EBE0
Olive · Brass · Field · Canvas
Standing out
Clear difference from cyber-blue. The military feel stands out without being aggressive. But olive-khaki could limit people's perception of what Strategic Cyber does beyond defence.
Being remembered
Distinctive but more subtle than the other two. The olive-brass pairing may not pop the way orange or ironbark would when seen alongside other logos.
First impression
Feels operational and defence-coded. Strong with people who value military alignment. Could feel too niche for Innovator clients who prefer cleaner, more modern looks.
Brand Element 02

Logo Concepts

Three concepts, each measured against the three things a good brand needs to do. Use the palette switcher to see how each logo works across colour systems.

Uplift

Stepping bars rising left to right — showing capability uplift and steady improvement.
Standing out
Clean and simple, but stepping-bar shapes are fairly common in growth-focused brands outside cyber. Good differentiation within the industry, less so outside it.
Being remembered
Very simple and easy to picture from memory. The ascending bars tell a clear story. Strongest recall of the three concepts.
First impression
Feels optimistic and approachable. The upward motion suggests growth. Both Manufacturers and Innovators read it positively.

Momentum

Nested chevrons showing forward motion and layered protection.
Standing out
The nested chevrons are distinctive, though chevrons do appear in defence branding. Good differentiation within cyber, moderate within broader defence.
Being remembered
Fairly easy to recall. The layered shapes are recognisable but a bit more complex than Uplift.
First impression
Feels dynamic and forward-moving. The layers suggest depth and multi-layered expertise. Appeals more to the Innovator ICP.

Convergence

Complex chevrons converging on a central arrow — multiple strengths focusing into decisive action.
Standing out
The most visually unique of the three. Nothing in the competitor set looks like this. Strongest differentiation by a clear margin.
Being remembered
More complex than the other two, but so distinctive that once seen, it's hard to confuse with anything else. Memorable through uniqueness.
First impression
Feels sophisticated and authoritative. The convergence motif suggests expertise coming together to create impact. Strong with Innovators, respected by Manufacturers.
Brand Element 03

Font Systems

Three font systems, each measured against the three things a good brand needs to do.

Strategic Cyber
Uplift. Protect. Accelerate.
We help Australian defence manufacturers and deep-tech innovators build cyber resilience that supports growth.
IRAP ASSESSED · DISP MEMBER · CLEARED PERSONNEL
Engineering Standard System A
Headline
Inter — Neo-grotesque sans-serif · Weight 700 · Tight letter-spacing (-0.02em) · Built for screen clarity
Body
DM Sans — Geometric sans-serif · Weight 400 · Large x-height · Great for reading on screens
Mono
JetBrains Mono — Developer-first monospace · Weight 400 · Ligature support · For technical labels and data
Standing out
Inter is widely used in tech, which makes it less distinctive. But the full combination with DM Sans and JetBrains Mono is less common and creates a cohesive system that stands apart from generic corporate fonts.
Being remembered
The easiest to read of all three systems. Clean, systematic, and smooth. When people can read your message without effort, they're more likely to remember what you said.
First impression
Feels modern, precise, and capable. Signals engineering quality without being cold. Innovators use these fonts in their own products. Manufacturers see it as clean and professional.
Strategic Cyber

IRAP ASSESSED · DISP MEMBER · CLEARED PERSONNEL
Defence Authority System B
Headline
Barlow Semi Condensed — Semi-condensed grotesk · Weight 700 · Narrow proportions · Commanding, military feel
Body
Source Sans 3 — Humanist sans-serif · Weight 400 · Adobe's open-source workhorse · Built for long documents
Mono
IBM Plex Mono — Corporate monospace · Weight 400 · IBM design heritage · Institutional, structured feel
Standing out
The semi-condensed headlines are less common in cyber branding and give a commanding, military feel. Good differentiation within the industry.
Being remembered
A bit harder to read than Engineering Standard because of the condensed proportions, which may reduce how much people retain. The distinctive headlines make up for it with strong visual recall.
First impression
Feels authoritative and institutional. The Barlow headlines carry weight. May feel too formal for Innovators but resonates strongly with defence-aligned Manufacturers.
Strategic Cyber
Uplift. Protect. Accelerate.
We help Australian defence manufacturers and deep-tech innovators build cyber resilience that supports growth.
IRAP ASSESSED · DISP MEMBER · CLEARED PERSONNEL
Industrial Grade System C
Headline
Archivo — Wide grotesque · Weight 700–800 · Broad letterforms · Heavy, industrial, stamped feel
Body
Work Sans — Geometric sans-serif · Weight 400 · Optimised for screen · Warm without being casual
Mono
Space Mono — Display monospace · Weight 400 · Editorial character · Designed for the web, not the terminal
Standing out
The most visually distinctive of the three systems. Archivo's wide, heavy letters are unmistakable and rarely seen in cyber. Strongest typographic differentiation.
Being remembered
The heavy weight makes headlines impossible to miss, but the wide shapes can slow down reading for longer content. Strong visual impact trades off with reading ease.
First impression
Feels heavy, industrial, and unapologetic. Like equipment branding stamped from steel. Strongly connects with Manufacturers. May feel too heavy for Innovators who prefer lighter type.
Our Recommendation

The combination we recommend

Logo

Convergence

Strategic Cyber
The most visually distinct of all three concepts. In a market where competitors default to shields and generic marks, Convergence is the logo most likely to be remembered — because nothing else in the space looks like it.
Colour Palette

Industrial Warm

The least visually extreme of the three palettes, but that's the point. It still breaks from the blue everyone else uses, while staying professional and approachable for any audience — Manufacturers, federal government, or Innovator startups.
Font System

Industrial Grade

Strategic Cyber
Cyber resilience for Australian defence.
IRAP ASSESSED · DISP MEMBER
The most distinct of the three font systems. Archivo's wide, heavy headlines stand out immediately — but the system is still easy to read where it counts. Work Sans keeps body text clean and comfortable, so the brand feels bold without sacrificing clarity.
Why this combination works
Convergence is the most visually distinct logo — so it's likely to have the strongest recall. Industrial Warm is the least extreme palette, but it still looks professional and approachable for any audience, whether they're a Manufacturer, in federal government, or an Innovator. Industrial Grade is the most distinctive font system — bold enough to stand out, but still easy to read where it matters. Together: a brand that stands out, sticks in memory, and feels right from the first touchpoint.
